But I'll tell it to you,

00:01:33.185 --> 00:01:35.551
Taylor series,
as we guys in the Physics

00:01:35.551 --> 00:01:40.708
Department tend to use it.
The philosophy of the Taylor

00:01:40.708 --> 00:01:46.169
series is the following:
That if some function

00:01:46.169 --> 00:01:52.480
f(x)--and I'm going to
draw that function,

00:01:52.480 --> 00:01:55.541
something like this--but I'm
going to imagine that you don't

00:01:55.541 --> 00:01:57.410
have access to the whole
function.

00:01:57.410 --> 00:02:01.778
You cannot see the whole thing.
You can only zero-in on a tiny

00:02:01.778 --> 00:02:05.730
region around here.
And the question is,

00:02:05.730 --> 00:02:11.300
as you try to build a good
approximation to the function,

00:02:11.300 --> 00:02:15.053
how will you set it up so that
you can write an approximation

00:02:15.053 --> 00:02:19.268
for this whole function,
valid near the point x =

00:02:19.268 --> 00:02:23.220
0, where you know something.
So, suppose I block out the

00:02:23.220 --> 00:02:25.939
whole function--you've got to
imagine mentally.

00:02:25.939 --> 00:02:28.210
I don't show you anything
except what's happening here.

00:02:28.210 --> 00:02:31.230
In other words,
I show you only f(0).

00:02:34.920 --> 00:02:39.250
That's all you're told.
The value of the function is 92.

00:02:39.250 --> 00:02:42.590
What should we do away from
x = 0?

00:02:42.590 --> 00:02:44.945
Well, you've got no information
about this function,

00:02:44.945 --> 00:02:47.440
you don't know if it's going
up, if it's going down.

00:02:47.440 --> 00:02:50.440
All I tell you is one number,
what it's doing now.

00:02:50.440 --> 00:02:53.617
It's clear the best
approximation you can make is a

00:02:53.617 --> 00:02:55.735
flat line.
There's no reason to tilt it

00:02:55.735 --> 00:02:58.349
one way or the other,
given the information you have.

00:02:58.349 --> 00:03:01.410
So, the first approximation of
the function you will say is,

00:03:01.410 --> 00:03:03.590
f(x) equal to that
[f(0)].

00:03:03.590 --> 00:03:07.608
It's not equal to;
you can put some symbol that

00:03:07.608 --> 00:03:11.868
means approximately equal to.
It's like saying,

00:03:11.868 --> 00:03:16.806
"Temperature today is 92,
now what's it going to be

00:03:16.806 --> 00:03:20.456
tomorrow?"
Well, if you don't know

00:03:20.456 --> 00:03:25.087
anything else,
you cannot tell what it's going

00:03:25.087 --> 00:03:28.473
to be tomorrow.
But if you know that this is

00:03:28.473 --> 00:03:30.991
fall, that the temperature's
always going down,

00:03:30.991 --> 00:03:33.839
and somebody tells you,
"I know the rate of change of

00:03:33.839 --> 00:03:36.183
temperature.
I know that as of today,

00:03:36.183 --> 00:03:39.069
the rate of change of
temperature is something."

00:03:39.069 --> 00:03:42.837
Then you can use that
information to make a prediction

00:03:42.837 --> 00:03:45.889
on what it will be tomorrow.
That is to say,

00:03:45.889 --> 00:03:48.280
for values of x not
equal to 0.

00:03:48.280 --> 00:03:52.137
And let's denote by this
following symbol:

00:03:52.137 --> 00:03:56.465
f prime of 0 is the
derivative, which is

00:03:56.465 --> 00:04:01.274
df/dx at x = 0.
And you'll multiply it by

00:04:01.274 --> 00:04:05.297
x, and that's your best
bet for what the function is,

00:04:05.297 --> 00:04:08.728
away from x = 0.
What that does is to

00:04:08.728 --> 00:04:13.454
approximate the function by a
straight line with the right

00:04:13.454 --> 00:04:17.316
intercept and the right slope.
By "right" I mean,

00:04:17.316 --> 00:04:20.319
matches what you know about the
exact function.

00:04:20.319 --> 00:04:24.466
And if it turns out the
function really was a straight

00:04:24.466 --> 00:04:27.801
line, you are done.
It's not even an approximation,

00:04:27.801 --> 00:04:30.529
it'll track the function all
the way to eternity.

00:04:30.529 --> 00:04:33.182
But it can happen,
of course, that the function

00:04:33.182 --> 00:04:36.354
decides to curve upwards,
as I've shown in this example,

00:04:36.354 --> 00:04:38.949
and this will not work if you
go too far.

00:04:38.949 --> 00:04:40.433
For a while,
you'll be tangent to the

00:04:40.433 --> 00:04:42.329
function, but then it'll bend
away from you.

00:04:42.329 --> 00:04:44.764
So, it's really good for a very
small x and you can say,

00:04:44.764 --> 00:04:47.160
"Well, I want to do a little
better when I go further out."

00:04:47.160 --> 00:04:50.571
Well, what this doesn't tell
you, this approximation,

00:04:50.571 --> 00:04:54.310
is that the rate of change
itself has a rate of change.

00:04:54.310 --> 00:04:57.097
This assumes the rate of change
is a fixed rate of change,

00:04:57.097 --> 00:04:59.250
which is the rate of change at
the origin.

00:04:59.250 --> 00:05:01.741
And the rate of change of the
rate of change is the second

00:05:01.741 --> 00:05:03.686
derivative.
So, if somebody told you,

00:05:03.686 --> 00:05:06.220
"Look, here's one more piece of
information."

00:05:06.220 --> 00:05:09.687
I know the second derivative of
the function,

00:05:09.687 --> 00:05:14.180
which I'm going to write as
f double prime at 0.

00:05:14.180 --> 00:05:16.539
Well, with that information,
you can build a better

00:05:16.539 --> 00:05:19.087
approximation to the function,
and you will put that in

00:05:19.087 --> 00:05:22.341
x^(2).
But the key thing is you've got

00:05:22.341 --> 00:05:25.900
to divide by 2,
but if you like 2 factorial.

00:05:30.350 --> 00:05:34.100
And the way you divide by the
2, because your goal is take

00:05:34.100 --> 00:05:38.115
this approximation and make sure
that that's whatever you know

00:05:38.115 --> 00:05:40.550
about the function built into
it.

00:05:40.550 --> 00:05:42.889
Right?
Let's check this approximation

00:05:42.889 --> 00:05:44.889
and see if it satisfies those
properties.

00:05:44.889 --> 00:05:47.205
First of all,
at x = 0,

00:05:47.205 --> 00:05:50.704
let's compare the two sides.
At x = 0,

00:05:50.704 --> 00:05:53.120
the left hand side is
f(0).

00:05:53.120 --> 00:05:55.709
On the right hand side,
when you put x = 0,

00:05:55.709 --> 00:05:58.300
you kill this and you kill this
and it matches.

00:05:58.300 --> 00:06:00.620
So, you've certainly got the
right value of the function.

00:06:00.620 --> 00:06:03.585
Then you say,
"What if I take the derivative

00:06:03.585 --> 00:06:06.000
of the function at x =
0?"

00:06:06.000 --> 00:06:08.566
Let's take the derivative of
this trial function,

00:06:08.566 --> 00:06:10.920
or the approximate function on
both sides.

00:06:10.920 --> 00:06:14.998
When I take the derivative,
that being a constant,

00:06:14.998 --> 00:06:20.957
does not contribute.
This derivative of x is

00:06:20.957 --> 00:06:22.328
1.
In the next one,

00:06:22.328 --> 00:06:24.905
the derivative of x^(2)
is 2x,

00:06:24.905 --> 00:06:28.141
2x cancels the 2,
so I get f double prime

00:06:28.141 --> 00:06:31.182
of 0 times x.
But now, evaluate the

00:06:31.182 --> 00:06:35.001
derivative at x = 0.
That gets rid of this guy,

00:06:35.001 --> 00:06:39.068
and the derivative of my test
function matches the derivative

00:06:39.068 --> 00:06:42.074
of the actual function,
because this is the actual

00:06:42.074 --> 00:06:43.750
derivative of the actual
function.

00:06:43.750 --> 00:06:47.735
Now, it follows that if you
want to say, "How about the

00:06:47.735 --> 00:06:50.540
second derivative of this
function?"

00:06:50.540 --> 00:06:54.649
let's take the test function I
have, or the approximation.

00:06:54.649 --> 00:06:57.578
Take a second derivative,
and make sure that comes out

00:06:57.578 --> 00:06:59.374
right.
I don't feel like writing this

00:06:59.374 --> 00:07:01.089
out, but try to do this in your
head.

00:07:01.089 --> 00:07:04.100
Take two derivatives on the
left-hand side and see what

00:07:04.100 --> 00:07:06.788
happens on the right hand side.
Well, if you take one

00:07:06.788 --> 00:07:09.415
derivative, this guy's gone.
If you take two derivatives,

00:07:09.415 --> 00:07:12.380
this guy's gone.
And then, if you take the first

00:07:12.380 --> 00:07:16.407
derivative, you get 2x,
you take the second derivative

00:07:16.407 --> 00:07:20.920
you get 2, the 2 cancels the 2.
Now, if you put x = 0.

00:07:20.920 --> 00:07:24.413
If you do, you find that
f(0) here matches the

00:07:24.413 --> 00:07:28.310
second derivative of the
function on the left-hand side.

00:07:28.310 --> 00:07:31.863
So, this 2 factorial is there
to make sure that the function

00:07:31.863 --> 00:07:35.477
you have cooked up has the right
value of the function at the

00:07:35.477 --> 00:07:37.622
origin,
has the right slope at the

00:07:37.622 --> 00:07:40.759
origin, has the right rate of
change of the slope at the

00:07:40.759 --> 00:07:42.736
origin.
Well, it's very clear what we

00:07:42.736 --> 00:07:45.507
should do.
If you had a whole bunch of

00:07:45.507 --> 00:07:49.898
derivatives, then the
approximation we will write will

00:07:49.898 --> 00:07:53.129
look like, f n-th
derivative.

00:07:53.129 --> 00:07:56.520
I cannot draw n primes
there, so n means

00:07:56.520 --> 00:07:59.718
n such primes,
x to the n over

00:07:59.718 --> 00:08:03.310
n factorial.
And you go as far as you can.

00:08:03.310 --> 00:08:06.730
If you know 13 derivatives,
put 13 derivatives here.

00:08:06.730 --> 00:08:10.325
That's an approximation.
That's not called a Taylor

00:08:10.325 --> 00:08:12.470
series, that's the approximation
to the function.

00:08:12.470 --> 00:08:16.595
Now, it may happen that
sometimes you hit the jackpot,

00:08:16.595 --> 00:08:19.319
and you know all the
derivatives.

00:08:19.319 --> 00:08:22.361
Someone tells you all the
derivatives of the function,

00:08:22.361 --> 00:08:24.850
then why stop?
Add them all up.

00:08:24.850 --> 00:08:29.653
Then, you will get the sum
going from the 0 derivative all

00:08:29.653 --> 00:08:33.634
the way up to infinity.
And if you do the summation of

00:08:33.634 --> 00:08:36.570
every value of x,
you will get a value,

00:08:36.570 --> 00:08:39.193
and if that summation is
meaningful and gives you a

00:08:39.193 --> 00:08:40.820
finite number,
that, in fact,

00:08:40.820 --> 00:08:43.540
is exactly the function you
were given.

00:08:43.540 --> 00:08:48.710
That is the Taylor series.
The Taylor series is a series

00:08:48.710 --> 00:08:52.412
of infinite number of terms
which, if you sum up -- and sum

00:08:52.412 --> 00:08:56.113
up to something sensible -- will
actually be as good as the

00:08:56.113 --> 00:08:59.900
left-hand side.
So, let me give you one example.

00:08:59.900 --> 00:09:04.436
Here's a famous example.
1 over 1 minus x is the

00:09:04.436 --> 00:09:07.943
real function.
You and I know this function,

00:09:07.943 --> 00:09:10.760
we know how to put it in a
calculator;

00:09:10.760 --> 00:09:13.285
we know how to plot it.
You give me an x and I

00:09:13.285 --> 00:09:15.270
stick it in the denominator,
subtract it from 1,

00:09:15.270 --> 00:09:17.529
invert it;
that's the function.

00:09:17.529 --> 00:09:20.784
But instead,
suppose this function was

00:09:20.784 --> 00:09:25.442
revealed to us in stages.
We were told f(0)--what

00:09:25.442 --> 00:09:29.267
is f(0) here?
Put the x equal to 0,

00:09:29.267 --> 00:09:32.935
f(0) is 1.
Now, let's take the derivative

00:09:32.935 --> 00:09:35.320
of this function,
df/dx.

00:09:35.320 --> 00:09:41.436
df/dx has a minus 1
because it's 1 minus x to

00:09:41.436 --> 00:09:46.485
the minus 1, times a square;
then the derivative of what's

00:09:46.485 --> 00:09:49.019
inside this, that gives you a
minus 1.

00:09:49.019 --> 00:09:52.604
This is simple calculus,
how to take the derivative of

00:09:52.604 --> 00:09:56.059
this fellow here.
Having taken the derivative,

00:09:56.059 --> 00:09:59.313
evaluate it at x = 0,
this vanishes,

00:09:59.313 --> 00:10:01.870
that becomes 1,
and you get 1.

00:10:01.870 --> 00:10:05.430
If you now take the second
derivative of this function,

00:10:05.430 --> 00:10:10.439
which I don't feel like doing,
and I evaluate that at x

00:10:10.439 --> 00:10:14.929
= 0, then I'll find it is equal
to 2 factorial.

00:10:14.929 --> 00:10:17.679
In fact, I'll find the
nth derivative at the

00:10:17.679 --> 00:10:21.940
origin to be n factorial.
Well, that's very nice.

00:10:21.940 --> 00:10:25.489
Because then,
my approximation to the

00:10:25.489 --> 00:10:30.321
function begins as 1 plus
x times the first

00:10:30.321 --> 00:10:33.656
derivative,
which happens to be 1 plus

00:10:33.656 --> 00:10:37.870
x^(2) over 2 factorial
times the second derivative,

00:10:37.870 --> 00:10:42.477
which happens to be 2 factorial
plus x^(3) over 3

00:10:42.477 --> 00:10:47.287
factorial times 3 factorial,
so you can see where this guy

00:10:47.287 --> 00:10:51.518
is going.
It looks like 1 + x + x^(2),

00:10:51.518 --> 00:10:56.640
et cetera.
The Taylor series is its

00:10:56.640 --> 00:10:59.823
infinite sum.
In practice,

00:10:59.823 --> 00:11:03.840
you may be happy to just keep a
couple of terms.

00:11:03.840 --> 00:11:07.144
So, let's get a feeling for
what those couple of terms can

00:11:07.144 --> 00:11:12.650
do for us.
So, let me take x = 0.1.

00:11:12.650 --> 00:11:18.398
x equal to point 1;
the real answer is 1 over 1

00:11:18.398 --> 00:11:22.097
minus point 1,
which is 1 over point 9,

00:11:22.097 --> 00:11:24.920
which is 1.1111,
etcetera.

00:11:24.920 --> 00:11:30.600
That's the target.
What do you do with the series?

00:11:30.600 --> 00:11:34.472
The series starts at 1,
times one-tenth,

00:11:34.472 --> 00:11:37.749
plus 1 over 100,
plus 1 over 1000,

00:11:37.749 --> 00:11:40.107
and so on.
And you can see,

00:11:40.107 --> 00:11:43.616
as I keep more and more terms,
I keep just filling up these

00:11:43.616 --> 00:11:46.811
ones.
If you stop at 1 over 1000,

00:11:46.811 --> 00:11:51.345
you stop right there.
So, this is the exact answer,

00:11:51.345 --> 00:11:54.417
this is the approximation.
But it's clear to you,

00:11:54.417 --> 00:11:56.808
perhaps in a simple example,
that if you kept all the terms

00:11:56.808 --> 00:11:59.649
of the series,
you really will get this

00:11:59.649 --> 00:12:02.680
infinite number of recurring
1's.

00:12:02.680 --> 00:12:06.417
So, that is the function.
That is the Taylor

00:12:06.417 --> 00:12:09.381
approximation.
We'll just chop it off whenever

00:12:09.381 --> 00:12:11.572
you want, and it's a good
approximation,

00:12:11.572 --> 00:12:15.820
and that's the Taylor series.
The series means sum everything.

00:12:15.820 --> 00:12:20.230
Now, summing an infinite number
of numbers is a delicate issue.

00:12:20.230 --> 00:12:22.965
I don't want to go there at
all, I discuss that in this math

00:12:22.965 --> 00:12:24.802
book.
But sometimes a sum makes no

00:12:24.802 --> 00:12:29.220
sense, then you've got to quit.
For example, put x = 2.

00:12:29.220 --> 00:12:35.529
The correct function is 1 - 2,
which is -1.

00:12:35.529 --> 00:12:44.580
Our approximation for x
= 2 looks like 1 + 2 + 4 + 8.

00:12:44.580 --> 00:12:46.580
Fist of all,
this sum is going to grow to

00:12:46.580 --> 00:12:49.679
infinity, because the numbers
are getting bigger and bigger.

00:12:49.679 --> 00:12:51.269
This sum seems to be all
positive;

00:12:51.269 --> 00:12:53.000
that is the correct answer is
negative.

00:12:53.000 --> 00:12:55.850
Obviously, the series doesn't
work.

00:12:55.850 --> 00:12:58.723
So, the next lesson of our
Taylor series is,

00:12:58.723 --> 00:13:02.332
you can write down the series,
but it may not sum up to

00:13:02.332 --> 00:13:05.340
anything sensible beyond a
certain range.

00:13:05.340 --> 00:13:08.105
So, if you're doing a Taylor
series at x = 0,

00:13:08.105 --> 00:13:10.870
and you go to x = 2,
it just doesn't work.

00:13:10.870 --> 00:13:13.220
So, you can ask,
"How far can I go from the

00:13:13.220 --> 00:13:15.394
origin?"
Well, in this simple example,

00:13:15.394 --> 00:13:18.289
we know that x = 1,
the function just going to

00:13:18.289 --> 00:13:20.850
infinity, that's why you
couldn't go there.

00:13:20.850 --> 00:13:24.409
And you cannot go to the
right-hand side of that point.

00:13:24.409 --> 00:13:26.662
The function is well defined on
the other side,

00:13:26.662 --> 00:13:28.914
but this series,
this knowledge of the function

00:13:28.914 --> 00:13:31.509
here, is not enough to get you
on the other side.

00:13:31.509 --> 00:13:36.114
So, this is a case where there
are obvious problems at x

00:13:36.114 --> 00:13:38.502
= 1.
But if I wrote a function like

00:13:38.502 --> 00:13:41.286
1 over 1 plus x^(2),
that's a nice function,

00:13:41.286 --> 00:13:44.818
got no troubles anywhere.
And yet, if you took the Taylor

00:13:44.818 --> 00:13:47.258
series for it,
you will find if you go beyond

00:13:47.258 --> 00:13:50.639
absolute value at x = 1,
the series makes no sense.

00:13:50.639 --> 00:13:54.789
So, I don't want to do that
mathematical theory of series.

00:13:54.789 --> 00:13:58.303
I just want to tell you that
functions can be approximated by

00:13:58.303 --> 00:14:00.098
series.
And if you're lucky,

00:14:00.098 --> 00:14:03.650
you can do the whole sum if you
know all the derivatives,

00:14:03.650 --> 00:14:07.330
and the whole sum may converge
to give a finite answer.

00:14:07.330 --> 00:14:09.529
In which case,
it's as good as the function.

00:14:09.529 --> 00:14:11.820
One guy can use 1over 1 minus
x;

00:14:11.820 --> 00:14:13.893
the other one can use the
infinite series,

00:14:13.893 --> 00:14:16.524
and they're morally and
mathematically in every sense

00:14:16.524 --> 00:14:18.692
equal,
as long as they don't stray

00:14:18.692 --> 00:14:22.080
outside the region of validity
of the infinite series.

00:14:22.080 --> 00:14:27.724
Ok, so the most popular example
that I've been using in the

00:14:27.724 --> 00:14:31.519
class, remember,
is 1 + x^(n).

00:14:31.519 --> 00:14:34.950
That's a function we can do
with Taylor series.

00:14:34.950 --> 00:14:39.783
f(0) is 1.
What's the derivative of the

00:14:39.783 --> 00:14:42.269
function?
It's n times 1 plus

00:14:42.269 --> 00:14:46.915
x^(n) minus 1.
The x is n times

00:14:46.915 --> 00:14:52.262
1 plus x^(n) minus 1;
if I evaluate it at x =

00:14:52.262 --> 00:14:55.418
0, it is just n.
That's why we get this famous

00:14:55.418 --> 00:14:57.330
result we've been using all the
time.

00:14:57.330 --> 00:15:00.660
If x is small enough you
stop there, because the next

00:15:00.660 --> 00:15:03.370
time it's going to involve an
x^(2) and an

00:15:03.370 --> 00:15:05.405
x^(3),
then if x is tiny,

00:15:05.405 --> 00:15:07.730
we have no respect for
x^(2) and x^(3),

00:15:07.730 --> 00:15:09.597
we just cut it off.
But if you want the next

00:15:09.597 --> 00:15:11.669
term--one of you guys even asked
me, "What happens next?"

00:15:11.669 --> 00:15:13.360
we'll take the second
derivative.

00:15:13.360 --> 00:15:17.515
You can see it's n times n
minus 1, times 1 plus x^(n)

00:15:17.515 --> 00:15:19.882
minus 2.
If you put x = 0,

00:15:19.882 --> 00:15:22.652
you'll get n times
n minus 1,

00:15:22.652 --> 00:15:24.960
x^(2),
and don't forget the 2

00:15:24.960 --> 00:15:28.078
factorial.
So, what I've been doing is

00:15:28.078 --> 00:15:30.916
I've been saying 1 plus
x^(n),

00:15:30.916 --> 00:15:34.805
approximately equal to this.
But even if you keep that,

00:15:34.805 --> 00:15:37.360
it's still approximate.
But it's a good approximation;

00:15:37.360 --> 00:15:41.039
how many terms you want to keep
depends on how tiny x is.

00:15:41.039 --> 00:15:44.517
Ok, so it's good to know
there's an infinite series,

00:15:44.517 --> 00:15:48.677
but it's also good to know you
can chop it off and do business

00:15:48.677 --> 00:15:52.750
with a few terms.
In fact, all of relativity we

00:15:52.750 --> 00:15:56.705
reduce as follows.
The energy of a particle is

00:15:56.705 --> 00:16:01.157
this, which we can write as
mc^(2) times 1 minus

00:16:01.157 --> 00:16:05.279
v^(2) over c^(2)
to the minus ½.

00:16:05.279 --> 00:16:09.150
If you expand this in a power
series, you're going to get

00:16:09.150 --> 00:16:11.570
mc^(2) + ½
mv^(2),

00:16:11.570 --> 00:16:14.922
plus stuff involving v
to the 4th over c to the

00:16:14.922 --> 00:16:17.740
4th times c^(2).
We dropped all this,

00:16:17.740 --> 00:16:21.361
and for 300 years we did
mechanics keeping just this

00:16:21.361 --> 00:16:23.792
term.
We just kept that first

00:16:23.792 --> 00:16:27.517
non-trivial term,
and all of our collisions and

00:16:27.517 --> 00:16:30.999
so on that we did,
used only that up to that

00:16:30.999 --> 00:16:33.134
point.
So, the approximations have

00:16:33.134 --> 00:16:35.116
really been useful,
and they describe nature

00:16:35.116 --> 00:16:36.857
approximately.
If you say, "Well,

00:16:36.857 --> 00:16:39.570
I want to be exact," you can go
back and use this.

00:16:39.570 --> 00:16:41.415
Unfortunately,
generally somebody tells you,

00:16:41.415 --> 00:16:43.469
"That's not exactly.
There in quantum mechanics,

00:16:43.469 --> 00:16:44.990
tells you the whole thing is
wrong."

00:16:44.990 --> 00:16:46.901
At every stage,
you will have to give up

00:16:46.901 --> 00:16:49.389
something.
So, I have a lot of respect for

00:16:49.389 --> 00:16:51.741
approximations.
If you could not describe the

00:16:51.741 --> 00:16:54.010
world approximately,
you couldn't have come where

00:16:54.010 --> 00:16:56.403
you've come.
Because no one knows the exact

00:16:56.403 --> 00:16:58.759
answer to a single question you
can pose.

00:16:58.759 --> 00:17:00.743
Ask me a question,
and the answer is,

00:17:00.743 --> 00:17:03.426
"I don't know."
Second part of the answer is,

00:17:03.426 --> 00:17:05.971
"Nobody knows."
Because if your question says

00:17:05.971 --> 00:17:09.080
give an answer to arbitrary
precision, any question asked,

00:17:09.080 --> 00:17:12.760
we just don't know.
Newtonian mechanics works for

00:17:12.760 --> 00:17:16.491
small velocities.
All of relativistic mechanics

00:17:16.491 --> 00:17:19.968
works for any velocity,
but not for really tiny

00:17:19.968 --> 00:17:22.241
objects.
Then you've got to use quantum

00:17:22.241 --> 00:17:25.228
mechanics.
So, always theories give way to

00:17:25.228 --> 00:17:28.638
new theories,
and so approximations are very

00:17:28.638 --> 00:17:30.880
important.
So, you have to learn this.

00:17:30.880 --> 00:17:36.755
Okay.
So now, I'm going to consider

00:17:36.755 --> 00:17:41.690
the following function:
e^(x).

00:17:48.660 --> 00:17:51.432
Now ,this guy is something you
all know and love,

00:17:51.432 --> 00:17:54.089
because it's one nice thing
about the function,

00:17:54.089 --> 00:17:56.400
is every derivative is
e^(x).

00:17:56.400 --> 00:17:59.349
Right?
Every child knows e^(x)

00:17:59.349 --> 00:18:02.030
has got e^(x) as its
derivative.

00:18:02.030 --> 00:18:05.112
Why do we like that here?
That means all the derivatives

00:18:05.112 --> 00:18:07.798
are sitting in front of you.
They're e^(x),

00:18:07.798 --> 00:18:10.621
and at x = 0,
e to the 0 is 1,

00:18:10.621 --> 00:18:14.173
so every derivative is 1.
And the function is very easy

00:18:14.173 --> 00:18:17.317
to write down.
It is really 1 + x +

00:18:17.317 --> 00:18:22.252
x^(2) over 2 factorial,
plus x to the 3 over 3

00:18:22.252 --> 00:18:26.349
factorial, x to the 4
over 4 factorial.

00:18:26.349 --> 00:18:28.915
You can go on like this,
and if you like to use a

00:18:28.915 --> 00:18:31.481
compact notation,
it's x^(n) over n

00:18:31.481 --> 00:18:34.651
factorial,
and going from 0 to infinity,

00:18:34.651 --> 00:18:37.740
that 0 factorial is defined to
be 1.

00:18:37.740 --> 00:18:42.864
That's e^(x).
If you ever forget the value of

00:18:42.864 --> 00:18:46.779
e, and I need to know the
value of e,

00:18:46.779 --> 00:18:50.365
because when I lock my suitcase
and check it into the airport,

00:18:50.365 --> 00:18:52.539
I use either e or
π,

00:18:52.539 --> 00:18:55.429
because they're the only two
numbers I can remember--So,

00:18:55.429 --> 00:18:57.319
if I forget the value of
e,

00:18:57.319 --> 00:19:02.445
I just say e is the same
as e to the 1,

00:19:02.445 --> 00:19:06.289
so I've got 1 + 1 + 1 + 2 + 1
over 6,

00:19:06.289 --> 00:19:10.623
and pretty soon I'm telling the
guy scanning my luggage,

00:19:10.623 --> 00:19:14.132
"That's my code."
And it's much better than any

00:19:14.132 --> 00:19:17.185
other code because I cannot
reconstruct, say,

00:19:17.185 --> 00:19:19.930
my grandfather's name.
I may not get it right.

00:19:19.930 --> 00:19:22.630
I may not construct my house
address, or my phone address.

00:19:22.630 --> 00:19:25.373
This doesn't change.
I've been moving around all

00:19:25.373 --> 00:19:27.849
over the world,
this is a very reliable number.

00:19:27.849 --> 00:19:30.565
Now, π is a good
number, but rules for computing

00:19:30.565 --> 00:19:32.539
π are somewhat more
difficult.

00:19:32.539 --> 00:19:35.003
π also can be computed
as an infinite series,

00:19:35.003 --> 00:19:37.947
but this guy is very easy.
There's 2 point in 7-7

00:19:37.947 --> 00:19:41.390
something, that is e.
Okay.

00:19:41.390 --> 00:19:44.240
Now, here is the very nice
property of this series.

00:19:44.240 --> 00:19:48.293
It is good for any x.
You remember the series for 1

00:19:48.293 --> 00:19:52.040
over 1 minus x crashed
and burned at x = 1.

00:19:52.040 --> 00:19:56.137
This series -- always good.
You put x = 37 million,

00:19:56.137 --> 00:19:59.008
you've got 37 million,
37 million cubed,

00:19:59.008 --> 00:20:02.410
37 million at the 4th power;
don't worry.

00:20:02.410 --> 00:20:05.429
These factorials downstairs
will tame it down and make it

00:20:05.429 --> 00:20:08.556
converge, and will give you
e to the whatever number

00:20:08.556 --> 00:20:10.573
I give.
That's something I'm not

00:20:10.573 --> 00:20:12.946
proving, but the series for
e^(x),

00:20:12.946 --> 00:20:16.259
no limits on validity.
All right.

00:20:16.259 --> 00:20:18.279
Then, we take the function,
cos x.

00:20:18.279 --> 00:20:24.560
Now, cos x,
we all know and love as this

00:20:24.560 --> 00:20:26.428
guy.
That's got a period of

00:20:26.428 --> 00:20:29.416
2π.
But we can write a series for

00:20:29.416 --> 00:20:33.157
it because it's a function.
And what do I need to know to

00:20:33.157 --> 00:20:35.936
write the series for it?
I need to know the value of the

00:20:35.936 --> 00:20:39.619
function at the origin.
So, we know cosine of 0 is 1.

00:20:39.619 --> 00:20:45.064
If you take the derivative you
get minus sine,

00:20:45.064 --> 00:20:50.168
and its value at 0 is 0.
You take one more derivative,

00:20:50.168 --> 00:20:52.869
you get minus cosine 0,
which is minus 1,

00:20:52.869 --> 00:20:55.569
and I think by now you get the
point.

00:20:55.569 --> 00:20:58.923
Every other derivative will
vanish, and the remaining

00:20:58.923 --> 00:21:02.470
derivatives will alternate in
sine from 1 to minus 1.

00:21:02.470 --> 00:21:04.868
That means, if you crank it
out, you will get 1,

00:21:04.868 --> 00:21:07.573
you won't have anything linear
in x because the

00:21:07.573 --> 00:21:10.380
coefficient of that is
sin 0 which vanishes;

00:21:10.380 --> 00:21:13.818
then you'll get x^(2)
over 2 factorial plus x

00:21:13.818 --> 00:21:16.130
to the 4 over 4 factorial,
and so on.

00:21:21.060 --> 00:21:25.686
This is cos x.
If you cut it off after some

00:21:25.686 --> 00:21:30.059
number of terms,
it's not going to work.

00:21:30.059 --> 00:21:31.927
In the beginning,
1 minus x^(2) looks very

00:21:31.927 --> 00:21:33.626
good.
This is 1 minus x^(2)

00:21:33.626 --> 00:21:35.664
over 2, looks like this.
But eventually,

00:21:35.664 --> 00:21:38.775
this approximation will go bad
on you, because x to the

00:21:38.775 --> 00:21:41.890
4th is just x to the 4th.
It'll grow without limit.

00:21:41.890 --> 00:21:44.624
No one's telling you this
approximation has a property

00:21:44.624 --> 00:21:47.588
that cosine is less than 1.
It doesn't satisfy that,

00:21:47.588 --> 00:21:50.769
because you're not supposed to
use it that far out.

00:21:50.769 --> 00:21:53.813
But if you keep all the terms,
then in fact,

00:21:53.813 --> 00:21:57.210
even though x to the 4th
is taking off,

00:21:57.210 --> 00:21:58.925
x to the minus 6 is
saying hey, come down,

00:21:58.925 --> 00:22:00.319
x to the 8th is saying,
go up.

00:22:00.319 --> 00:22:03.827
You add them all together,
remarkably, you will reproduce

00:22:03.827 --> 00:22:07.101
this function.
Very hard to imagine that the

00:22:07.101 --> 00:22:10.860
cosine that we know as
oscillatory is really this

00:22:10.860 --> 00:22:13.528
function.
And I hope all of you know

00:22:13.528 --> 00:22:16.119
enough to know how to find the
series.

00:22:16.119 --> 00:22:19.214
You should know the derivative
of cosine is minus sine,

00:22:19.214 --> 00:22:21.220
the derivative of sine is
cosine.

00:22:21.220 --> 00:22:24.359
And evaluate them at the origin;
I say you can build up the

00:22:24.359 --> 00:22:27.130
series.
Then, if you do similar tricks

00:22:27.130 --> 00:22:29.549
for sin x,
sin of 0 is 0,

00:22:29.549 --> 00:22:32.827
derivative of sin is cosine,
and of course,

00:22:32.827 --> 00:22:36.050
n of 0 is 1.
So, the first derivative is 1;

00:22:36.050 --> 00:22:38.367
that gives you this term.
Next one won't give you

00:22:38.367 --> 00:22:40.547
anything, the one after that
will give you this,

00:22:40.547 --> 00:22:42.450
and this guy will go on like
this one.

00:22:47.800 --> 00:22:50.206
Okay.
So, these are series for

00:22:50.206 --> 00:22:51.741
e^(x),
cos x,

00:22:51.741 --> 00:22:54.279
and sin x,
good for all x.

00:22:54.279 --> 00:22:56.320
So, there's no restriction on
this.

00:23:02.210 --> 00:23:05.437
One of the really interesting
things to do when you are bored,

00:23:05.437 --> 00:23:08.242
or stranded somewhere in an
airport, is to take cosine

00:23:08.242 --> 00:23:11.383
squared plus sine squared.
Squared the whole thing,

00:23:11.383 --> 00:23:14.750
add the squared of the whole
thing and add them up.

00:23:14.750 --> 00:23:16.842
You'll find,
by miracle, you will get the

00:23:16.842 --> 00:23:19.877
one from squaring the one and
every other power of x

00:23:19.877 --> 00:23:22.447
will keep on vanishing.
Of course, you'll have to

00:23:22.447 --> 00:23:24.900
collect powers of x by
expanding the bracket.

00:23:24.900 --> 00:23:27.449
But it will all cancel.
That's what I meant by saying

00:23:27.449 --> 00:23:29.299
this series is as good as this
function.

00:23:29.299 --> 00:23:32.130
It will obey all the identities
known.

00:23:32.130 --> 00:23:36.539
Okay.
Now, for the punch line.

00:23:36.539 --> 00:23:39.596
I think everyone--Some of you
may know what the punch line is,

00:23:39.596 --> 00:23:41.299
the punch line is the
following.

00:23:41.299 --> 00:23:45.188
Let us introduce,
without any preamble right now,

00:23:45.188 --> 00:23:49.077
the number i,
which is the squared root of

00:23:49.077 --> 00:23:52.148
minus 1.
All I expect of i is

00:23:52.148 --> 00:23:55.180
that when I squared it,
I get minus 1.

00:23:55.180 --> 00:23:59.304
If I cube it,
i^(3) is i^(2)

00:23:59.304 --> 00:24:03.630
times i,
so that's minus i,

00:24:03.630 --> 00:24:07.607
and i to the 4th is back
to plus 1 because i to

00:24:07.607 --> 00:24:10.590
the 4th is i^(2) times
i^(2),

00:24:10.590 --> 00:24:13.461
and i^(2) is minus 1.
So, if you take powers of

00:24:13.461 --> 00:24:15.789
i, it'll keep jumping
between these values.

00:24:15.789 --> 00:24:17.292
It'll be i,
it'll become minus 1,

00:24:17.292 --> 00:24:19.450
it'll become minus i,
then it'll become plus 1.

00:24:19.450 --> 00:24:22.599
That's the set of possible
values for powers of i.

00:24:22.599 --> 00:24:24.250
It'll be one of these four
values.

00:24:24.250 --> 00:24:29.052
Well.
Then we are told,

00:24:29.052 --> 00:24:36.437
if you now consider the
following rather strange object,

00:24:36.437 --> 00:24:40.019
e^(ix).
Now, e^(ix),

00:24:40.019 --> 00:24:42.619
you have to agree,
is really bizarre.

00:24:42.619 --> 00:24:45.557
e is some number,
you want to raise it to 2,

00:24:45.557 --> 00:24:47.839
that's fine.
Number times number.

00:24:47.839 --> 00:24:50.440
i is a strange number,
right?

00:24:50.440 --> 00:24:54.497
It's the squared root of minus
1, and you wanted me to raise

00:24:54.497 --> 00:24:58.259
e to a complex power.
What does that even mean?

00:24:58.259 --> 00:25:01.410
Multiply e by itself
ix times?

00:25:01.410 --> 00:25:03.880
Well, that definition of powers
is no good.

00:25:03.880 --> 00:25:08.878
But the series for e^(x)
defines it for all x,

00:25:08.878 --> 00:25:13.113
then we boldly define
e^(x) for even complex

00:25:13.113 --> 00:25:17.180
values of x as simply
this thing too,

00:25:17.180 --> 00:25:19.670
with ix plugged in place
of x.

00:25:19.670 --> 00:25:23.240
And by that fashion,
we define exponential.

00:25:23.240 --> 00:25:27.372
So, the exponential function is
simply defined as,

00:25:27.372 --> 00:25:31.589
suppose you write e
raised to dog.

00:25:31.589 --> 00:25:35.958
e raised to dog
is 1 plus dog plus

00:25:35.958 --> 00:25:39.994
dog^(2) over 2.
e raised to anything is

00:25:39.994 --> 00:25:43.095
a code for this series.
And now we raise e to

00:25:43.095 --> 00:25:44.584
various things.
Real numbers,

00:25:44.584 --> 00:25:46.970
complex numbers,
matrices, whatever you want.

00:25:46.970 --> 00:25:49.956
Your pet, you can put that up.
Of course, you've got to be a

00:25:49.956 --> 00:25:51.514
little careful.
You cannot raise e

00:25:51.514 --> 00:25:53.559
raised to dog,
because the units don't match.

00:25:53.559 --> 00:25:56.365
But there's a dog here
and dog^(2),

00:25:56.365 --> 00:25:59.346
so you should divide it by some
standard dog,

00:25:59.346 --> 00:26:01.450
like President's dog
[laughter].

00:26:01.450 --> 00:26:03.113
Take some standard.
Napoleon's dog,

00:26:03.113 --> 00:26:04.923
divide it, then you've got
something dimensionless

00:26:04.923 --> 00:26:06.859
[laughter].
Then it will work.

00:26:06.859 --> 00:26:09.901
So, as long as it's some
dimensionless object,

00:26:09.901 --> 00:26:13.279
this is what we mean by
e raised to that.

00:26:13.279 --> 00:26:17.079
That's a fantastic leap of
imagination.

00:26:17.079 --> 00:26:20.070
How to raise e to
whatever power you like;

00:26:20.070 --> 00:26:21.970
take the series.
Let's do the series.

00:26:21.970 --> 00:26:29.208
So, I'm going to get 1 plus
ix, plus (ix)^(2)

00:26:29.208 --> 00:26:33.097
over 2 factorial,
plus (ix)^(3) over 3

00:26:33.097 --> 00:26:36.190
factorial, and I'm going to stop
after this last term,

00:26:36.190 --> 00:26:38.730
(ix)^(4) over 4
factorial.

00:26:38.730 --> 00:26:41.920
Keep going, then what do you
get?

00:26:41.920 --> 00:26:47.319
Let's take the 1 from here,
leave this alone for a minute.

00:26:47.319 --> 00:26:50.788
You write i times
x, go here,

00:26:50.788 --> 00:26:54.999
i^(2) is minus 1,
so I get minus x^(2)

00:26:54.999 --> 00:26:58.220
over 2 factorial,
then I come here.

00:26:58.220 --> 00:27:01.469
I cubed is minus i,
so I write here,

00:27:01.469 --> 00:27:04.410
minus x^(3) over 3
factorial.

00:27:04.410 --> 00:27:07.102
Then, I go back here and write
x to the 4th over 4

00:27:07.102 --> 00:27:09.337
factorial.
By now, everybody knows what's

00:27:09.337 --> 00:27:12.238
going on.
Everybody knows that this is

00:27:12.238 --> 00:27:14.670
just cos x + i sin x.

00:27:19.299 --> 00:27:22.270
Okay, this is a super duper
formula.

00:27:22.270 --> 00:27:26.867
Life cannot go on without this.
You want to draw a box around

00:27:26.867 --> 00:27:30.274
this one, draw it.
Because without this formula,

00:27:30.274 --> 00:27:32.610
we cannot do so many things we
do.

00:27:37.960 --> 00:27:41.693
It says that the trigonometric
functions and the exponential

00:27:41.693 --> 00:27:44.920
functions are actually very
intimately connected.

00:27:44.920 --> 00:27:47.379
And if they're all defined by
the power series,

00:27:47.379 --> 00:27:50.322
you're able to prove it.
So, this is the formula proven

00:27:50.322 --> 00:27:53.029
by Euler.
And it's considered a very

00:27:53.029 --> 00:27:56.903
beautiful formula,
and here is the particularly

00:27:56.903 --> 00:28:00.440
beautiful special case of this
formula.

00:28:00.440 --> 00:28:05.028
If you put x = π,
I get the result e^(iπ)

00:28:05.028 --> 00:28:08.388
equal the cos π,
which is minus 1,

00:28:08.388 --> 00:28:11.420
plus i sin π,
which is 0.

00:28:11.420 --> 00:28:17.259
I get the result e^(iπ)
+ 1 = 0.

00:28:17.259 --> 00:28:20.976
Now, everybody agrees this has
got to be one of the most

00:28:20.976 --> 00:28:24.828
beautiful formulas you can
imagine involving numbers or in

00:28:24.828 --> 00:28:28.200
mathematics.
Why is it such a great formula?

00:28:28.200 --> 00:28:31.918
Look at this formula here.
π, defined from the

00:28:31.918 --> 00:28:34.731
Egyptian times,
is a ratio of circle to

00:28:34.731 --> 00:28:37.551
diameter.
i is square root to

00:28:37.551 --> 00:28:39.980
minus 1.
1 is the basis for all integers.

00:28:39.980 --> 00:28:42.200
e is the basis for the
logarithm.

00:28:42.200 --> 00:28:46.484
Here is a formula in which all
the key numbers appear in one

00:28:46.484 --> 00:28:50.058
single compact formula.
The fact that these numbers

00:28:50.058 --> 00:28:53.054
would have a relationship at all
is staggering,

00:28:53.054 --> 00:28:56.049
and this is the nature of the
relationship.

00:28:56.049 --> 00:29:00.557
This is voted the formula most
likely to be remembered,

00:29:00.557 --> 00:29:03.210
this formula.
Now, we are going to use not

00:29:03.210 --> 00:29:05.710
only the special case,
but we are going to use this

00:29:05.710 --> 00:29:10.420
all the time.
So, how many people have seen

00:29:10.420 --> 00:29:14.170
this?
Okay.

00:29:14.170 --> 00:29:16.930
If you have not seen this,
then you've got more work than

00:29:16.930 --> 00:29:19.677
people who have seen this.
You've got to go and you've got

00:29:19.677 --> 00:29:22.500
to do all the intermediate steps
so you get used to this thing.

00:29:22.500 --> 00:29:25.380
Now, let's do the following two
other variations,

00:29:25.380 --> 00:29:29.210
and then I'll move on.
If I change x to minus

00:29:29.210 --> 00:29:32.259
x, then I get
e^(-ix).

00:29:32.259 --> 00:29:34.858
Cosine of minus x is
cosine x,

00:29:34.858 --> 00:29:37.880
and sin of minus x is
minus sin x.

00:29:37.880 --> 00:29:39.320
So, I can get that relation.

00:29:43.809 --> 00:29:48.736
Then, I'm going to combine
those two to do the following:

00:29:48.736 --> 00:29:53.222
I'm going to say that cos
x = e^(ix) +

00:29:53.222 --> 00:29:57.369
e^(-ix) over 2,
you can check that.

00:29:57.369 --> 00:30:05.153
And sin x =
e^(ix) - e^(-ix)

00:30:05.153 --> 00:30:09.869
over 2i.
You just add and subtract these

00:30:09.869 --> 00:30:11.830
two formulas and you get that.

00:30:19.800 --> 00:30:23.039
Okay.
So, what does this mean?

00:30:23.039 --> 00:30:26.730
It means that trigonometric
functions, you don't need them.

00:30:26.730 --> 00:30:29.136
If you've got exponential
functions, you can manufacture

00:30:29.136 --> 00:30:30.799
trigonometric functions out of
them,

00:30:30.799 --> 00:30:34.686
provided you're not afraid to
go to exponents with complex

00:30:34.686 --> 00:30:38.850
number i in them.
And all the identities about

00:30:38.850 --> 00:30:42.349
sines and cosines will follow
from this.

00:30:42.349 --> 00:30:44.924
For example,
if you take cosine squared plus

00:30:44.924 --> 00:30:47.380
sine squared,
you're supposed to get 1.

00:30:47.380 --> 00:30:50.028
Well, you can square the right
hand side, you can square the

00:30:50.028 --> 00:30:51.690
left hand side,
and you will get 1.

00:30:51.690 --> 00:30:54.210
To get the 1,
you better remember the

00:30:54.210 --> 00:30:58.130
following: e^(ix) times
e^(-ix) is what?

00:31:01.559 --> 00:31:03.319
You know how you come by an
exponent?

00:31:03.319 --> 00:31:07.659
You raise it to one power times
the same thing raised to another

00:31:07.659 --> 00:31:11.516
power, is e raised to ix minus
x, which is e raised to 0,

00:31:11.516 --> 00:31:14.460
which is 1.
So, when you raise the number

00:31:14.460 --> 00:31:18.280
to a power, you multiply it by
the number times a different

00:31:18.280 --> 00:31:22.430
power, the product is a number
to the sum of the two powers.

00:31:22.430 --> 00:31:25.907
Powers combine.
2 cubed times 2 to the 4th is 2

00:31:25.907 --> 00:31:28.200
to the 6th.
That's true for 2;

00:31:28.200 --> 00:31:29.859
it's true for e;
it's true for everything.

00:31:29.859 --> 00:31:33.197
Exponents add when you multiply
them, that's why e^(ix)

00:31:33.197 --> 00:31:35.549
and e^(-ix) combine to
give you 1.

00:31:35.549 --> 00:31:37.990
Once you know that,
you can prove this.

00:31:37.990 --> 00:31:44.876
Okay.
Now, I'm going to do a little

00:31:44.876 --> 00:31:49.041
more of complex numbers,
so maybe I'll leave this alone

00:31:49.041 --> 00:31:51.742
for now.
I introduced you the number

00:31:51.742 --> 00:31:55.309
i by saying it's the
square root of minus 1,

00:31:55.309 --> 00:31:59.839
and complex numbers entered our
life, even though we didn't go

00:31:59.839 --> 00:32:02.920
looking for them.
You can write down equations

00:32:02.920 --> 00:32:06.202
with real numbers with no
intention of invoking anything

00:32:06.202 --> 00:32:08.938
fancy,
like this, and you find there

00:32:08.938 --> 00:32:12.918
is no solution to this equation.
Even though everything there is

00:32:12.918 --> 00:32:15.016
completely real.
So, you can say,

00:32:15.016 --> 00:32:19.597
"Well, x^(2) is minus
1," and you can manufacture a

00:32:19.597 --> 00:32:23.375
number i,
with a property i^(2) is

00:32:23.375 --> 00:32:25.205
minus 1;
then, of course,

00:32:25.205 --> 00:32:28.199
you can have x equal to
plus and minus i as your

00:32:28.199 --> 00:32:30.339
answer.
So, complex numbers arose by

00:32:30.339 --> 00:32:32.519
trying to solve quadratic
equations.

00:32:32.519 --> 00:32:37.977
So, let me write you a slightly
more interesting quadratic

00:32:37.977 --> 00:32:41.519
equation, x^(2) + x + 1 =
0.

00:32:41.519 --> 00:32:45.059
So, there's no funny business,
all real numbers.

00:32:45.059 --> 00:32:51.650
We want to solve this equation,
so we go back to our good old

00:32:51.650 --> 00:32:58.461
sandbox days when we knew what
the answer for this was--minus 3

00:32:58.461 --> 00:33:01.024
over 2.
And we already have a problem

00:33:01.024 --> 00:33:03.920
because we don't know what to do
with square root of minus 3.

00:33:03.920 --> 00:33:10.896
So, we will write it as square
root of minus 1 times square

00:33:10.896 --> 00:33:14.046
root of 3.
Square root of minus 1 we will

00:33:14.046 --> 00:33:16.492
call i,
and we will say this equation

00:33:16.492 --> 00:33:20.271
has two roots.
x plus/minus (there are

00:33:20.271 --> 00:33:25.705
) two roots, which are minus 1
plus or minus square root of

00:33:25.705 --> 00:33:31.229
3i over 2.
So, one root is 1 minus 1,

00:33:31.229 --> 00:33:37.785
plus root 3i over 2.
And the other root is minus 1

00:33:37.785 --> 00:33:43.833
minus root 3i over 2.
These are solutions formerly to

00:33:43.833 --> 00:33:48.029
this equation in the following
sense.

00:33:48.029 --> 00:33:49.759
Take this x that I'm
giving you;

00:33:49.759 --> 00:33:53.216
put that into that equation,
square the x and add the

00:33:53.216 --> 00:33:54.915
x to it,
and add the 1,

00:33:54.915 --> 00:33:57.200
it'll in fact satisfy the
equation.

00:33:57.200 --> 00:34:00.228
All you will have to know when
you manipulate it is that

00:34:00.228 --> 00:34:02.997
i^(2) is minus 1.
Using the one property,

00:34:02.997 --> 00:34:05.440
you can now solve the quadratic
equation.

00:34:05.440 --> 00:34:08.818
So, people realize if you
enlarge numbers to include

00:34:08.818 --> 00:34:11.336
complex numbers,
then you can solve any

00:34:11.336 --> 00:34:14.980
polynomial equation with that
many number of roots.

00:34:14.980 --> 00:34:16.609
If it's quadratic,
it'll have two roots,

00:34:16.609 --> 00:34:18.280
if it's cubic,
it'll have three roots.

00:34:18.280 --> 00:34:21.646
They may not all be real;
they may involve the complex

00:34:21.646 --> 00:34:25.513
number i.
Now, a very important point to

00:34:25.513 --> 00:34:30.889
notice is that this whole thing,
minus 1 plus root 3i

00:34:30.889 --> 00:34:35.809
over 2, the whole thing is a
single complex number.

00:34:35.809 --> 00:34:37.280
Don't think of it as the sum of
two numbers;

00:34:37.280 --> 00:34:39.884
it's a single complex number.
For example,

00:34:39.884 --> 00:34:44.787
if this had been plus instead
of minus, you'd get something

00:34:44.787 --> 00:34:48.000
like 1 plus or minus root 3 over
2.

00:34:48.000 --> 00:34:50.817
Take the positive root,
you don't think of it as two

00:34:50.817 --> 00:34:52.980
numbers.
This is a single number.

00:34:52.980 --> 00:34:56.760
And that continues to be true
even if it's a complex number.

00:34:56.760 --> 00:35:00.904
So, you should think of the
whole combination as a single

00:35:00.904 --> 00:35:05.123
entity which you can add to
others as entities and square,

00:35:05.123 --> 00:35:07.070
and so on.
Okay.

00:35:07.070 --> 00:35:08.960
So, that's what we are going to
do now.

00:35:08.960 --> 00:35:14.030
We're going to generalize this
particular case and introduce

00:35:14.030 --> 00:35:18.431
now a complex number z.
And we're going to write every

00:35:18.431 --> 00:35:21.733
complex number z as a
part that has no i in it,

00:35:21.733 --> 00:35:23.989
and a part that has an i
in it.

00:35:23.989 --> 00:35:29.327
The example I had here,
x is equal to--in this

00:35:29.327 --> 00:35:35.486
example, x was minus 1
over 2 and y was plus or

00:35:35.486 --> 00:35:39.471
minus root 3 over 2.
And we're going to visualize

00:35:39.471 --> 00:35:42.460
that complex number as a point
in the xy plane.

00:35:42.460 --> 00:35:45.131
We just measure x
horizontally and y

00:35:45.131 --> 00:35:48.131
vertically, put a dot there,
that's your complex number,

00:35:48.131 --> 00:35:48.840
z.

00:35:54.300 --> 00:35:58.128
Then, we say the new complex
number called z star [*]

00:35:58.128 --> 00:36:02.399
and it's defined to be x -
iy, is called the complex

00:36:02.399 --> 00:36:03.430
conjugate;

00:36:07.610 --> 00:36:11.494
complex conjugate of z.
It's obtained by changing the

00:36:11.494 --> 00:36:13.484
sign of i.
So, if you like,

00:36:13.484 --> 00:36:16.486
if z is sitting here,
z star is sitting there,

00:36:16.486 --> 00:36:18.420
reflected around the x
axis.

00:36:27.239 --> 00:36:31.130
So, how does one work with
complex numbers?

00:36:31.130 --> 00:36:32.977
You add them,
you subtract them,

00:36:32.977 --> 00:36:35.659
and you multiply them,
and you divide them.

00:36:35.659 --> 00:36:38.290
If you know how to do that,
you can do with complex numbers

00:36:38.290 --> 00:36:40.059
everything you did with real
numbers.

00:36:40.059 --> 00:36:44.120
So if z_1 is a
complex number that is equal to

00:36:44.120 --> 00:36:46.739
x_1 +
iy_1,

00:36:46.739 --> 00:36:49.461
and z_2 is a
complex number that is

00:36:49.461 --> 00:36:51.969
x_2 +
iy_2,

00:36:51.969 --> 00:36:55.187
we will define
z_1 +

00:36:55.187 --> 00:36:59.477
z_2 to be
x_1 +

00:36:59.477 --> 00:37:03.052
x_2 times
i times

00:37:03.052 --> 00:37:07.789
y_1 plus
y_2.

00:37:07.789 --> 00:37:11.217
If you draw pictures,
then if z_1 is

00:37:11.217 --> 00:37:14.052
that number and
z_2 is that

00:37:14.052 --> 00:37:17.235
number [pointing to the board],
then z_1 +

00:37:17.235 --> 00:37:19.019
z_2 it really
is like adding vectors.

00:37:19.019 --> 00:37:22.880
This number is z_1
+ z_2.

00:37:22.880 --> 00:37:25.269
It's exactly like adding
vectors.

00:37:25.269 --> 00:37:30.597
But you don't think of this
plus that as two disjoined

00:37:30.597 --> 00:37:34.820
numbers, but as forming a single
entity.

00:37:34.820 --> 00:37:41.171
In a complex number z,
x is called a real part

00:37:41.171 --> 00:37:47.199
of z, and is denoted by
symbol "real z."

00:37:47.199 --> 00:37:50.176
If you want to get z,
if you want to get the real

00:37:50.176 --> 00:37:53.206
part of a complex number
z, you add to its complex

00:37:53.206 --> 00:37:56.830
conjugate and divide by 2.
Because you are adding x +

00:37:56.830 --> 00:38:00.209
iy to x - iy,
you get 2x and you

00:38:00.209 --> 00:38:04.172
divide by 2, you get that.
If you want to get the

00:38:04.172 --> 00:38:09.167
y, which is called the
imaginary part of z,

00:38:09.167 --> 00:38:13.360
you take z - z star and divide
by 2i.

00:38:13.360 --> 00:38:19.010
It's like saying find the
x component of a vector.

00:38:19.010 --> 00:38:20.440
It's whatever multiplies
i.

00:38:20.440 --> 00:38:22.690
y component of a vector
is whatever multiplies j.

00:38:22.690 --> 00:38:25.549
Similarly, a complex number can
be broken down into the part

00:38:25.549 --> 00:38:28.360
which is real and the part that
multiplies the i.

00:38:28.360 --> 00:38:30.852
To extract the real part,
add to it the conjugate divided

00:38:30.852 --> 00:38:33.611
by 2, to extract the imaginary
part, subtract the conjugate and

00:38:33.611 --> 00:38:37.574
divide by 2i.
Again, if you have seen this,

00:38:37.574 --> 00:38:40.654
you don't need this.
If you haven't seen it,

00:38:40.654 --> 00:38:43.903
it may look a little fast.
But that's why I posted all the

00:38:43.903 --> 00:38:47.348
notes on the website,
chapter 5 from this math book,

00:38:47.348 --> 00:38:51.222
which has got all this stuff.
So, you can go home and you can

00:38:51.222 --> 00:38:54.877
read it.
Ok, the next question is what

00:38:54.877 --> 00:39:00.539
is z_1 times
z_2?

00:39:00.539 --> 00:39:03.780
Well, that's very easy to
calculate.

00:39:03.780 --> 00:39:06.602
x_1 +
iy_1 times

00:39:06.602 --> 00:39:09.760
x_2 +
iy_2.

00:39:09.760 --> 00:39:12.881
Just open all the brackets and
remember i^(2) is minus

00:39:12.881 --> 00:39:14.530
1.
That's all you've got to do.

00:39:14.530 --> 00:39:15.819
So, that gives me
x_1x

00:39:15.819 --> 00:39:17.827
_2;
then, let me multiply the

00:39:17.827 --> 00:39:20.659
iy_1 times the
iy_2.

00:39:20.659 --> 00:39:23.253
And that gives me minus
y_1y

00:39:23.253 --> 00:39:26.365
_2,
because i^(2) is minus 1

00:39:26.365 --> 00:39:28.699
plus i times
x_1y

00:39:28.699 --> 00:39:30.969
_2 +
x_2y

00:39:30.969 --> 00:39:33.971
_1.
This is how you multiply two

00:39:33.971 --> 00:39:34.810
complex numbers.

00:39:39.440 --> 00:39:43.023
That's something very nice that
happens when you multiply a

00:39:43.023 --> 00:39:45.679
number z by its complex
conjugate.

00:39:45.679 --> 00:39:49.675
What happens when you multiply
z by its conjugate,

00:39:49.675 --> 00:39:52.100
you are saying,
take x + iy,

00:39:52.100 --> 00:39:55.239
multiply it by x minus
iy;

00:39:55.239 --> 00:39:59.039
a + b times a - b =
a^(2) - b^(2).

00:39:59.039 --> 00:40:01.460
But remember,
b is iy.

00:40:01.460 --> 00:40:05.220
So, when you take the square of
that, you should keep track of

00:40:05.220 --> 00:40:08.920
all the signs and you will find
it's x^(2) + y^(2).

00:40:08.920 --> 00:40:15.278
We denote that as this,
and this thing is called the

00:40:15.278 --> 00:40:19.830
modulus of z [|z|].
It's the length of the complex

00:40:19.830 --> 00:40:21.280
number z,
just given by Pythagoras'

00:40:21.280 --> 00:40:21.670
theorem.

00:40:30.789 --> 00:40:32.945
You should know,
whenever you take a complex

00:40:32.945 --> 00:40:34.800
number, multiply by each
conjugate,

00:40:34.800 --> 00:40:37.695
by its complex conjugate,
the result will be a real

00:40:37.695 --> 00:40:40.822
number equal to the square of
the length of the complex

00:40:40.822 --> 00:40:43.473
number.
Because I'm going to use that

00:40:43.473 --> 00:40:46.181
now to do the last of the
manipulations,

00:40:46.181 --> 00:40:49.514
which is, what is
z_1 divided by

00:40:49.514 --> 00:40:53.151
z_2?
How do you divide these crazy

00:40:53.151 --> 00:40:55.254
numbers?
So, on the top I write

00:40:55.254 --> 00:40:57.835
x_1 +
iy_1,

00:40:57.835 --> 00:41:00.416
the bottom, I write
x_2 +

00:41:00.416 --> 00:41:02.974
iy_2.
If I only had

00:41:02.974 --> 00:41:05.970
x_2,
I know how to divide.

00:41:05.970 --> 00:41:07.661
It's just a number.
Divide that by

00:41:07.661 --> 00:41:09.239
x_2 and that by
x_2.

00:41:09.239 --> 00:41:11.237
But I've got the sum of these
two numbers in the bottom,

00:41:11.237 --> 00:41:12.980
and you can ask,
"How do you do the division?"

00:41:12.980 --> 00:41:15.980
So, the trick,
always, when you run into this

00:41:15.980 --> 00:41:19.800
problem, is to multiply the top
and bottom by the complex

00:41:19.800 --> 00:41:23.044
conjugate of the bottom.
Multiply it by x_2

00:41:23.044 --> 00:41:24.680
- iy_2,
top and bottom.

00:41:28.610 --> 00:41:30.920
Then, something nice happens to
the denominator,

00:41:30.920 --> 00:41:33.771
because the denominator then
becomes x_2^(2) +

00:41:33.771 --> 00:41:36.566
y_2^(2),
which is an ordinary real

00:41:36.566 --> 00:41:38.750
number, nothing complex about
that.

00:41:38.750 --> 00:41:40.889
The numerator,
you can open out the brackets.

00:41:40.889 --> 00:41:42.159
I don't know if I want to do
that;

00:41:42.159 --> 00:41:47.011
it's just going to be
x_1x_2 +

00:41:47.011 --> 00:41:52.328
y_1y_2 +
i times y_1x

00:41:52.328 --> 00:41:55.594
_2 -
y_2x

00:41:55.594 --> 00:41:59.101
_1.
Now, don't worry about all the

00:41:59.101 --> 00:42:00.329
details.
All it means is,

00:42:00.329 --> 00:42:02.737
if you know how to multiply two
complex numbers,

00:42:02.737 --> 00:42:04.940
you can also divide by a
complex number.

00:42:04.940 --> 00:42:07.309
That's the key point.
Why?

00:42:07.309 --> 00:42:09.506
Because if you've got a complex
number denominator,

00:42:09.506 --> 00:42:11.616
you don't like it,
