00:42:43.500 --> 00:42:50.590
Now, why did I do all that
stuff today about e^(ix)?

00:42:50.590 --> 00:42:54.693
You're going to see that now.
The rationale for going through

00:42:54.693 --> 00:42:59.640
that math is the following.
Let's take this complex number

00:42:59.640 --> 00:43:04.719
that goes from here to here,
that is x + iy.

00:43:04.719 --> 00:43:08.307
And let's introduce,
just like we would for an

00:43:08.307 --> 00:43:11.895
ordinary vector,
this angle θ and that

00:43:11.895 --> 00:43:15.098
length r.
Whenever you have a vector,

00:43:15.098 --> 00:43:18.136
you can talk about the
Cartesian components x

00:43:18.136 --> 00:43:20.186
and y,
or you can talk about the

00:43:20.186 --> 00:43:22.159
length of the vector and the
angle it makes.

00:43:22.159 --> 00:43:26.668
Then, it's clear that x = r
cos θ, and y = r sin

00:43:26.668 --> 00:43:31.020
θ, where θ is now
an angle associated with a

00:43:31.020 --> 00:43:35.840
complex number which tells you
at what angle it's located,

00:43:35.840 --> 00:43:37.840
and r is the length of
the complex number.

00:43:37.840 --> 00:43:40.940
It's called the polar form of
the complex number.

00:43:40.940 --> 00:43:45.356
Then, you can see that
z, which is x +

00:43:45.356 --> 00:43:50.807
iy, is equal to r
times cos θ + i sin θ

00:43:50.807 --> 00:43:56.539
which you can now write as
r times e^(iθ).

00:43:56.539 --> 00:44:00.068
That's why we did all that
work, to tell you that a complex

00:44:00.068 --> 00:44:02.320
number can be written in this
form.

00:44:02.320 --> 00:44:06.065
You can either write this x
+ iy, or else

00:44:06.065 --> 00:44:09.044
re^(iθ).
They both talk about the same

00:44:09.044 --> 00:44:10.920
number.
One talks about how much real

00:44:10.920 --> 00:44:14.070
part and how much imaginary part
it has, other way of writing it

00:44:14.070 --> 00:44:15.970
talks about how long the vector
is,

00:44:15.970 --> 00:44:19.329
and at what angle it is located.
It contains the same

00:44:19.329 --> 00:44:21.904
information.
So, that r is equal to--

00:44:21.904 --> 00:44:25.514
the inverse of this formula is
that r is square root of

00:44:25.514 --> 00:44:28.000
x squared plus y
squared,

00:44:28.000 --> 00:44:33.139
and θ is tan
inverse y over x.

00:44:33.139 --> 00:44:35.012
In other words,
tan θ is y over

00:44:35.012 --> 00:44:36.542
x.
This is y,

00:44:36.542 --> 00:44:37.930
and this is x.

00:44:43.159 --> 00:44:46.403
Now, the advantage of writing a
complex number in polar form is

00:44:46.403 --> 00:44:49.065
the following.
Suppose I give you two complex

00:44:49.065 --> 00:44:51.621
numbers, z_1 is
r_1e

00:44:51.621 --> 00:44:54.864
^(iθ)_1,
and z_2 is

00:44:54.864 --> 00:44:56.510
r_2
e^(iθ

00:44:56.510 --> 00:44:59.017
)_2.
The product z_1z

00:44:59.017 --> 00:45:02.325
_2 is very easy to
calculate in this form because

00:45:02.325 --> 00:45:04.726
r_1r
_2 multiply to

00:45:04.726 --> 00:45:08.800
give you this,
and the exponentials combine.

00:45:08.800 --> 00:45:13.701
It's a lot easier to multiply
them in this form than when I

00:45:13.701 --> 00:45:17.525
multiplied them somewhere here.
See, if I write it in this

00:45:17.525 --> 00:45:18.840
Cartesian form,
it's a big mess.

00:45:18.840 --> 00:45:21.748
In polar form, it's very easy.
So, the rule is,

00:45:21.748 --> 00:45:25.171
if you want to multiply two
numbers, multiply the lengths to

00:45:25.171 --> 00:45:28.711
get the length of the new number
and add the angles to get the

00:45:28.711 --> 00:45:32.040
angle of the product.
So, what I'm telling you is

00:45:32.040 --> 00:45:35.884
that if z_1
looks like this guy with some

00:45:35.884 --> 00:45:38.651
