pick any A you like.
Think about what that means.

00:55:56.660 --> 00:55:59.664
What is the meaning of A?
A is the amount by which

00:55:59.664 --> 00:56:01.139
you pulled it when you let it
go.

00:56:01.139 --> 00:56:05.299
You are told whether you pull
the spring by one inch or by ten

00:56:05.299 --> 00:56:09.118
inches, the time it takes to
finish a full back and forth

00:56:09.118 --> 00:56:11.710
motion is independent of
A.

00:56:11.710 --> 00:56:15.210
This frequency here is
independent of A.

00:56:15.210 --> 00:56:16.848
Yes?
Student:

00:56:16.848 --> 00:56:18.693
[inaudible]
Professor Ramamurti

00:56:18.693 --> 00:56:23.150
Shankar: This t here?
Here?

00:56:23.150 --> 00:56:23.619
Student:
[inaudible]

00:56:23.619 --> 00:56:24.306
Professor Ramamurti
Shankar: Ah,

00:56:24.306 --> 00:56:25.140
very good.
That's correct.

00:56:25.140 --> 00:56:26.773
So, let's be careful.
This is the t axis

00:56:26.773 --> 00:56:29.242
[pointing at graph on board];
this is a particular time,

00:56:29.242 --> 00:56:30.400
capital T.

00:56:36.070 --> 00:56:39.442
So, the remarkable property of
simple harmonic motion is that

00:56:39.442 --> 00:56:42.309
the amplitude does not determine
the time period.

00:56:42.309 --> 00:56:44.777
If you pull it by two inches,
compared to one inch,

00:56:44.777 --> 00:56:47.929
it's got a long way to go.
But because you pulled it by

00:56:47.929 --> 00:56:51.719
two inches, the spring is going
to be that much more tense,

00:56:51.719 --> 00:56:54.439
and it's going to exert a
bigger force so that it'll go

00:56:54.439 --> 00:56:57.750
faster for most of the time,
that's very clear.

00:56:57.750 --> 00:57:00.742
But the fact that it goes
faster in exactly the right way

00:57:00.742 --> 00:57:02.880
to complete the trip at the same
time,

00:57:02.880 --> 00:57:06.824
is rather a miraculous property
of the fact that this equation

00:57:06.824 --> 00:57:10.242
has this particular form.
If you tamper with this,

00:57:10.242 --> 00:57:13.934
if you add to this a little
bit, like 1 over 100 times

00:57:13.934 --> 00:57:17.070
x^(3),
then all these bets are off.

00:57:17.070 --> 00:57:21.310
It's got to be that equation
for that result to be true.

00:57:21.310 --> 00:57:23.977
Okay.
So, this is simple harmonic

00:57:23.977 --> 00:57:26.278
motion.
Then, you can do the following

00:57:26.278 --> 00:57:29.519
variant of this solution,
which I will write down now.

00:57:29.519 --> 00:57:36.019
Suppose I set my clock to 0,
right there.

00:57:36.019 --> 00:57:38.370
You set your clock to 0 here,
but I can say,

00:57:38.370 --> 00:57:40.609
"You know what?
I just got up and I'm looking

00:57:40.609 --> 00:57:42.190
at the mass, I set my clock to
0."

00:57:42.190 --> 00:57:44.369
When it hits 0,
it's not at the maximum.

00:57:44.369 --> 00:57:47.650
But it's the same physics,
it's the same equation.

00:57:47.650 --> 00:57:51.311
And that really comes from the
fact that we had one more

00:57:51.311 --> 00:57:54.840
latitude here of adding a
certain number φ,

00:57:54.840 --> 00:57:58.530
which is called a "phase," to
the oscillator.

00:57:58.530 --> 00:58:03.599
Whatever you pick for
φ, it'll still work.

00:58:03.599 --> 00:58:05.286
And whatever you pick for
capital A,

00:58:05.286 --> 00:58:07.400
it'll still work.
So, whenever you have an

00:58:07.400 --> 00:58:09.876
oscillator, namely,
a mass and spring system,

00:58:09.876 --> 00:58:12.971
and you want to know what
x is going to be at all

00:58:12.971 --> 00:58:16.114
times,
you need to somehow determine

00:58:16.114 --> 00:58:19.833
the amplitude and the phase.
Once you know that,

00:58:19.833 --> 00:58:22.850
you can calculate x at
all future times.

00:58:22.850 --> 00:58:28.828
So, let me give you an example.
Suppose an oscillator has

00:58:28.828 --> 00:58:35.910
x = 5 and velocity equal
to 0, at t equal to 0.

00:58:35.910 --> 00:58:39.554
So what does that mean?
I pulled it by 5 and I let it

00:58:39.554 --> 00:58:41.547
go.
I tell you the spring constant

00:58:41.547 --> 00:58:43.865
k and I tell you the
mass, and I say,

00:58:43.865 --> 00:58:46.898
"What's the future x?"
You've got to come back to this

00:58:46.898 --> 00:58:50.425
equation.
And you've got to say,

00:58:50.425 --> 00:58:55.790
5 = A cosine of 0 +
φ.

00:58:55.790 --> 00:58:59.230
And how about the velocity?
Velocity is supposed to be 0;

00:58:59.230 --> 00:59:05.140
that is minus ΩA sin
Ωt + φ.

00:59:05.140 --> 00:59:09.170
But t is 0.
So, that tells me 0 is minus

00:59:09.170 --> 00:59:12.500
Ω a sin φ.
Ω is not 0,

00:59:12.500 --> 00:59:16.266
A is not 0.
Therefore sin φ is 0,

00:59:16.266 --> 00:59:20.596
that means φ is 0 if
you get rid of that,

00:59:20.596 --> 00:59:25.920
so the subsequent motion is
x = 5 cos Ωt.

00:59:25.920 --> 00:59:28.440
This is a problem where we did
not need φ.

00:59:28.440 --> 00:59:32.244
But it could have been that
when you joined the experiment,

00:59:32.244 --> 00:59:35.081
you were somewhere here;
then, the mass is actually

00:59:35.081 --> 00:59:36.975
moving.
Then I will say at t =

00:59:36.975 --> 00:59:38.840
0, velocity was some other
number.

00:59:38.840 --> 00:59:41.311
Maybe 6.
Then, you've got to go back and

00:59:41.311 --> 00:59:43.297
write two equations.
One for x:

00:59:43.297 --> 00:59:47.044
take the derivative which looks
like this, and instead of

00:59:47.044 --> 00:59:50.034
putting 0, you put 6.
You've got two unknowns,

00:59:50.034 --> 00:59:52.481
A and φ.
You've got to juggle them

00:59:52.481 --> 00:59:54.943
around, and you've got to solve
for A and φ,

00:59:54.943 --> 00:59:57.982
given these two numbers.
It's a simple exercise to solve

00:59:57.982 --> 01:00:01.218
for them, and when you do,
you have completely fit the

01:00:01.218 --> 01:00:02.739
problem.
In other words,

01:00:02.739 --> 01:00:05.966
simply to be told a mass is
connected to a spring of known

01:00:05.966 --> 01:00:09.364
mass and force constant is not
enough to determine the future

01:00:09.364 --> 01:00:11.926
of the spring.
You have to be told--For

01:00:11.926 --> 01:00:15.457
example, if nobody pulled the
mass, it's just going to sit

01:00:15.457 --> 01:00:17.572
there forever.
If you pulled it by 10,

01:00:17.572 --> 01:00:20.019
it's going to go back and forth
from 10 to minus 10.

01:00:20.019 --> 01:00:23.915
So, you have to be told further
information to nail down these

01:00:23.915 --> 01:00:26.354
two numbers.
They're called free parameters

01:00:26.354 --> 01:00:28.272
in the solution.
On the other hand,

01:00:28.272 --> 01:00:31.515
no matter how much you pulled
it and how you released it,

01:00:31.515 --> 01:00:34.005
this Ω,
and therefore the frequency,

01:00:34.005 --> 01:00:36.039
are not variable.
Yes?

01:00:36.039 --> 01:00:37.860
Student:
[inaudible]

01:00:37.860 --> 01:00:41.570
Professor Ramamurti
Shankar: If you start it at

01:00:41.570 --> 01:00:43.735
rest,
indeed, it will be 0,

01:00:43.735 --> 01:00:47.758
because the velocity at
t = 0 is minus ΩA sin

01:00:47.758 --> 01:00:49.561
φ.
If you want to kill that,

01:00:49.561 --> 01:00:52.361
the only way is φ = 0.
You could put φ = π if

01:00:52.361 --> 01:00:54.260
you like, but if you put 0,
that'll do.

01:00:58.950 --> 01:01:02.264
Okay.
So, this is the elementary

01:01:02.264 --> 01:01:05.916
parts of this thing.
And I already told you the

01:01:05.916 --> 01:01:09.781
following things.
If x(t) is equal to

01:01:09.781 --> 01:01:14.860
A cos Ωt--let's
put φ = 0.

01:01:14.860 --> 01:01:17.250
In other words,
we'll agree that since there's

01:01:17.250 --> 01:01:19.694
only one oscillator,
it is perverse to set your

01:01:19.694 --> 01:01:22.775
clock to 0 at any time other
than when the oscillator is at

01:01:22.775 --> 01:01:25.673
one extreme point.
If there are two oscillators

01:01:25.673 --> 01:01:28.398
oscillating out of step,
it's impossible to make

01:01:28.398 --> 01:01:31.534
φ = 0 for both of them.
Because if you can sync your

01:01:31.534 --> 01:01:33.988
clock when one of them is at a
maximum, that may not be when

01:01:33.988 --> 01:01:36.684
the other one's at a maximum.
But with one oscillator,

01:01:36.684 --> 01:01:39.300
to choose φ other than
0 is perverse.

01:01:39.300 --> 01:01:41.307
It's like saying,
"I'm doing a projectile

01:01:41.307 --> 01:01:43.776
problem.
I'll pick the place where I

01:01:43.776 --> 01:01:46.690
launch the projectile to be x =
y = 0."

01:01:46.690 --> 01:01:49.389
You can pick some other crazy
origin, but it doesn't help.

01:01:49.389 --> 01:01:52.380
So, we'll assume φ is 0
in this problem.

01:01:52.380 --> 01:01:55.780
If that is x,
what is velocity at time

01:01:55.780 --> 01:01:59.117
t?
Take the derivative of this,

01:01:59.117 --> 01:02:02.849
you get minus Ω A
sin Ωt.

01:02:02.849 --> 01:02:07.170
That means the velocity is also
oscillating sinusiodally but the

01:02:07.170 --> 01:02:11.010
amplitude for oscillation is
Ω times A.

01:02:11.010 --> 01:02:13.543
So, if A is the range of
variation for x,

01:02:13.543 --> 01:02:16.639
Ω times A is the
range of variation for velocity.

01:02:16.639 --> 01:02:19.612
Velocity will go all the way
from plus Ω A to minus

01:02:19.612 --> 01:02:21.488
Ω A.
The acceleration,

01:02:21.488 --> 01:02:24.690
which is one more derivative,
is minus Ω

01:02:24.690 --> 01:02:26.869
^(2)A,
cos Ωt.

01:02:26.869 --> 01:02:30.989
Which is really minus Ω
^(2) times x itself.

01:02:30.989 --> 01:02:35.455
So, the amplitude for
oscillation for the acceleration

01:02:35.455 --> 01:02:39.035
is Ω^(2) times A.
So, I think you should

01:02:39.035 --> 01:02:41.349
understand if Ω is very
large;

01:02:41.349 --> 01:02:44.425
then, the velocity will have
very big excursions and the

01:02:44.425 --> 01:02:47.110
acceleration will have even
bigger excursions,

01:02:47.110 --> 01:02:49.925
because the range of,
this A really means if

01:02:49.925 --> 01:02:52.739
you plot x,
it's going to look like this,

01:02:52.739 --> 01:02:54.550
going from A to minus
A.

01:02:54.550 --> 01:02:58.235
This says if you plot the
velocity, it's going to look

01:02:58.235 --> 01:03:01.239
like this.
The range will go from Ω

01:03:01.239 --> 01:03:04.502
A to minus Ω A.
If you plot the acceleration,

01:03:04.502 --> 01:03:06.537
it'll go from Ω
^(2)A to minus Ω

01:03:06.537 --> 01:03:07.140
^(2)A.

01:03:11.400 --> 01:03:15.460
Last thing you want to verify
is the Law of Conservation of

01:03:15.460 --> 01:03:17.643
Energy.
I think I mentioned this to you

01:03:17.643 --> 01:03:20.049
when I studied energy,
but let me repeat one more

01:03:20.049 --> 01:03:21.544
time.
If you take,

01:03:21.544 --> 01:03:24.826
in this problem,
½ mv^(2) +½

01:03:24.826 --> 01:03:30.570
kx^(2)--I did that for
you--You can also verify this.

01:03:30.570 --> 01:03:34.671
Okay?
½ kx^(2) is going to

01:03:34.671 --> 01:03:39.489
involve A^(2) cosine
squared Ωt.

01:03:39.489 --> 01:03:41.842
½ mv^(2) is going to
involve something,

01:03:41.842 --> 01:03:43.989
something, something sin^(2)
Ωt.

01:03:43.989 --> 01:03:45.418
And by magic,
sin^(2) and

01:03:45.418 --> 01:03:47.630
cos^(2) will have the
same coefficient,

01:03:47.630 --> 01:03:50.645
so you can use the identity to
set them equal to 1,

01:03:50.645 --> 01:03:53.600
and get an answer that does not
depend on time.

01:03:53.600 --> 01:03:56.209
That's the beauty.
Even though position and

01:03:56.209 --> 01:03:59.020
velocity are constantly
changing, this combination,

01:03:59.020 --> 01:04:01.720
if you crank it out,
will not depend on time.

01:04:01.720 --> 01:04:05.558
And what can it possibly be?
If it doesn't depend on time,

01:04:05.558 --> 01:04:07.320
I can calculate it whenever I
like.

01:04:07.320 --> 01:04:11.215
So, let me go to the instant
when the mass has reached one

01:04:11.215 --> 01:04:13.880
extremity and is about to swing
back.

01:04:13.880 --> 01:04:16.360
At that instant it has no
velocity;

01:04:16.360 --> 01:04:19.146
it only has an x,
which is equal to amplitude,

01:04:19.146 --> 01:04:21.414
or motion.
So, that's the energy of an

01:04:21.414 --> 01:04:24.415
oscillator, ½ kA^(2).
When v = 0,

01:04:24.415 --> 01:04:27.935
x will be plus or minus
A, but any other

01:04:27.935 --> 01:04:30.858
intermediate point you can find
the velocity,

01:04:30.858 --> 01:04:34.429
if you give me the x.
We did that too.

01:04:34.429 --> 01:04:41.280
So, this is all I want to say
about the linear oscillator.

01:04:41.280 --> 01:04:45.088
But let me mention to you
another kind of oscillation,

01:04:45.088 --> 01:04:50.909
which is very interesting.
Suppose you suspend a rod from

01:04:50.909 --> 01:04:55.679
the ceiling like this.
It's hanging there.

01:04:55.679 --> 01:05:00.051
If you give it a twist,
then it'll go twisting back and

01:05:00.051 --> 01:05:03.371
forth, like that.
That's also a simple harmonic

01:05:03.371 --> 01:05:06.810
motion, except what's varying
with time is not the linear

01:05:06.810 --> 01:05:09.086
coordinate,
but the angle θ by

01:05:09.086 --> 01:05:14.421
which the rod has been twisted.
What's the equation in this

01:05:14.421 --> 01:05:17.860
case?
The equation here is I,

01:05:17.860 --> 01:05:21.380
d 2θ over
dt^(2).

01:05:21.380 --> 01:05:23.829
You guys remember now,
that's the analog of ma?

01:05:23.829 --> 01:05:25.800
That's going to be equal to the
torque.

01:05:32.179 --> 01:05:35.349
Now, what'll happen in the
problems we consider is that

01:05:35.349 --> 01:05:39.238
θ is a small number,
and the torque will be such

01:05:39.238 --> 01:05:42.550
that it brings you back to
θ = 0.

01:05:42.550 --> 01:05:47.442
So, this number will be
approximately equal to minus

01:05:47.442 --> 01:05:51.280
some number κ times
θ.

01:05:51.280 --> 01:05:55.050
That's the analog of minus
kx.

01:05:55.050 --> 01:05:58.928
Little k was the
restoring force divided by the

01:05:58.928 --> 01:06:01.928
displacement,
which produced the restoring

01:06:01.928 --> 01:06:04.044
force.
Little κ is the

01:06:04.044 --> 01:06:07.836
restoring torque divided by the
angle at which you twisted it to

01:06:07.836 --> 01:06:12.130
get that torque.
So, this isn't always true.

01:06:12.130 --> 01:06:15.324
For small oscillations,
sin τ vanishes at

01:06:15.324 --> 01:06:17.688
θ = 0;
it will look like some number

01:06:17.688 --> 01:06:19.067
times θ.
If you like,

01:06:19.067 --> 01:06:21.900
it's the Taylor series for
τ for small angles.

01:06:21.900 --> 01:06:25.039
If you knew this κ you
are done, because

01:06:25.039 --> 01:06:27.911
mathematically,
this equation is the same as

01:06:27.911 --> 01:06:31.051
md 2 x over
dt^(2) is minus

01:06:31.051 --> 01:06:34.267
kx.
Because the Ω for this

01:06:34.267 --> 01:06:37.989
guy will be square root of
κ over I.

01:06:37.989 --> 01:06:40.682
You can steal the whole answer,
because mathematically,

01:06:40.682 --> 01:06:43.575
mathematicians don't care if
you're talking about θ

01:06:43.575 --> 01:06:45.570
or if you're talking about
x.

01:06:45.570 --> 01:06:49.146
Now, if you compare this
equation to this equation,

01:06:49.146 --> 01:06:52.938
md 2 x over
dt^(2) equal to minus

01:06:52.938 --> 01:06:55.539
kx,
if the Ω there was the

01:06:55.539 --> 01:06:58.633
root of k over m,
the Ω here would be

01:06:58.633 --> 01:07:02.410
root of κ over I.
So, you may be thinking,

01:07:02.410 --> 01:07:06.788
"Give me an example where
τ looks like κ

01:07:06.788 --> 01:07:09.078
times θ."
I'm going to give you that

01:07:09.078 --> 01:07:09.320
example.

01:07:21.360 --> 01:07:25.060
So, that example is going to be
the following simple pendulum.

01:07:31.760 --> 01:07:35.890
Take a pendulum like this.
It's got a mass m.

01:07:35.890 --> 01:07:38.710
It's got some length l;
it's hanging from the ceiling.

01:07:38.710 --> 01:07:41.115
It's a rigid rod,
not a string,

01:07:41.115 --> 01:07:43.360
but a rigid,
massless rod.

01:07:43.360 --> 01:07:46.179
And the mass m is at the
bottom.

01:07:46.179 --> 01:07:50.770
So, it's happy to hang like
this, but suppose you give it a

01:07:50.770 --> 01:07:54.966
kick, so you push it over there
to an angle θ,

01:07:54.966 --> 01:08:01.634
which is whatever you like.
What is the torque in this

01:08:01.634 --> 01:08:05.579
particular case?
Let's find out.

01:08:05.579 --> 01:08:08.888
The force is mg,
and the angle between the

01:08:08.888 --> 01:08:12.402
force--and you're trying to do
rotations around this

01:08:12.402 --> 01:08:15.780
point--this angle here is the
same θ.

01:08:15.780 --> 01:08:23.720
So, torque is really minus
mgl sin θ.

01:08:23.720 --> 01:08:28.811
That's the formula for torque.
It's the force times the

01:08:28.811 --> 01:08:32.549
distance of the lever arm or the
distance over which the force is

01:08:32.549 --> 01:08:36.112
from the rotation axis times the
sine of the angle between the

01:08:36.112 --> 01:08:39.850
direction of the force and the
direction of the separation.

01:08:39.850 --> 01:08:44.456
So, the equation for the
pendulum really is the

01:08:44.456 --> 01:08:50.765
following: Id^(2) θ over
dt^(2) is equal to minus

01:08:50.765 --> 01:08:56.621
mgl sin θ.
Now, we cannot do business with

01:08:56.621 --> 01:08:59.252
this equation.
This equation is a famous

01:08:59.252 --> 01:09:02.090
equation, but you and I don't
know how to solve it with what

01:09:02.090 --> 01:09:03.855
we know.
But we have learned,

01:09:03.855 --> 01:09:07.439
even earlier today--look at the
formula for sin x.

01:09:07.439 --> 01:09:10.267
Sin x begins with
x minus x^(3) over

01:09:10.267 --> 01:09:13.786
3 factorial, and so on.
So, if θ is small,

01:09:13.786 --> 01:09:16.649
then you may write
mglθ.

01:09:16.649 --> 01:09:20.113
So, for small angles,
sin θ is

01:09:20.113 --> 01:09:23.577
θ, and the restoring
torque, in fact,

01:09:23.577 --> 01:09:27.119
is linear in the angle of the
coordinate.

01:09:27.119 --> 01:09:31.449
So, by comparison now,
we know that this fellow is our

01:09:31.449 --> 01:09:34.229
κ.
So, κ for the pendulum

01:09:34.229 --> 01:09:36.329
is mgl.
So, κ may not be

01:09:36.329 --> 01:09:39.130
universal in every problem,
in each problem you've got to

01:09:39.130 --> 01:09:41.676
find κ.
You find that by moving the

01:09:41.676 --> 01:09:44.970
system off equilibrium,
finding the restoring torque,

01:09:44.970 --> 01:09:47.430
and if you're doing it right,
restoring torque will always

01:09:47.430 --> 01:09:49.764
look like something,
something, something times

01:09:49.764 --> 01:09:51.564
θ.
Everything multiplying

01:09:51.564 --> 01:09:55.259
θ is our κ.
So, let's now calculate

01:09:55.259 --> 01:09:58.529
Ω for the simple
pendulum.

01:09:58.529 --> 01:10:03.094
I've shown you this is
κ over I,

01:10:03.094 --> 01:10:07.720
and κ was mgl.
And what's I?

01:10:07.720 --> 01:10:13.560
It's equal to moment of inertia
of this mass around this point.

01:10:13.560 --> 01:10:16.314
The rod is massless.
For a single point mass,

01:10:16.314 --> 01:10:18.556
we know the moment of inertia
is just m times

01:10:18.556 --> 01:10:21.555
l^(2).
So, you find Ω is equal

01:10:21.555 --> 01:10:26.221
to square root of g over
l, and that is 2π

01:10:26.221 --> 01:10:29.308
over T.
So, you get back the famous

01:10:29.308 --> 01:10:32.627
formula you learned,
T is 2π square

01:10:32.627 --> 01:10:37.555
root of l over g.
This is the origin of the

01:10:37.555 --> 01:10:42.087
formula you learned in school.
It comes from small

01:10:42.087 --> 01:10:47.170
oscillations of a pendulum.
So, think about this problem.

01:10:47.170 --> 01:10:50.579
If you pulled a pendulum by an
angle so large that sin

01:10:50.579 --> 01:10:53.478
θ is no longer
approximated by θ but

01:10:53.478 --> 01:10:57.001
you need a θ^(3) over 6
term -- it can happen for large

01:10:57.001 --> 01:11:00.723
enough θ – then,
the equation to solve is no

01:11:00.723 --> 01:11:03.320
longer this.
What that means is,

01:11:03.320 --> 01:11:08.537
if you took a real pendulum
with a massless rod and a bob at

01:11:08.537 --> 01:11:11.361
the end,
the time it takes to finish an

01:11:11.361 --> 01:11:14.569
oscillation, in fact,
will depend on the amplitude.

01:11:14.569 --> 01:11:16.735
But only for small
oscillations,

01:11:16.735 --> 01:11:20.787
when sin θ can
be approximated by θ,

01:11:20.787 --> 01:11:24.909
you will find whether you do
that the time is the same.

01:11:24.909 --> 01:11:27.561
But if you go too far,
the other terms in sin

01:11:27.561 --> 01:11:30.162
θ will kick in,
and the result is no longer

01:11:30.162 --> 01:11:31.776
true.
The period of a pendulum,

01:11:31.776 --> 01:11:34.345
in fact, is not just a function
of l and g,

01:11:34.345 --> 01:11:36.180
but also a function of the
amplitude.

01:11:36.180 --> 01:11:40.079
Only for small amplitudes,
you get this marvelous result.

